fields.label_text:
Clare Twomey (born 1968)
‘Trophy’
2006
These 50 bluebirds are from a group of 4000
installed at the V&A in 2006. Clare Twomey
made each hand-finished bird using
Wedgwood’s famous blue Jasper clay.
She invited visitors to the installation to walk
among the birds and select one to take away,
a choice that prompted careful deliberation
of each bird’s individual qualities.
Made in London
Jasper, cast and hand-finished
Museum no. C.108:1 to 50-2007
Given by the artist

fields.descriptive_line: 'Trophy', 50 birds left from an installation of 4000 in the V&A in 2006, cast and hand finished Wedgewood blue Jasper clay, Clare Twomey, London, 2006
fields.physical_description: Fifty birds made of Wedgewood's famous blue Jasper clay, there is a variety of different colour blues, each bird is cast and then hand finished so each is individual.
fields.title: Trophy
fields.materials_techniques: Blue Jasper ware, cast, hand finished

fields.public_access_description:
Clare Twomey (born 1968)
‘Trophy’
2006
These 50 bluebirds are from a group of 4000 installed at the V&A in September 2006. Clare Twomey made each hand-finished bird using Wedgwood’s famous blue Jasper clay. She invited visitors to the installation to walk among the birds and take one away with them, this created a uniques opportunity for the visitors to have part of the collection. Twomey collaborated with Wedgewood in their production, attributing a sense of history and worth to each individual bird. Visitors were invited to send through images and excerpts of what happened to the birds when they had left the museum. 'Trophy' raised awareness of the diversity of ceramics and the role of the museum and how objects become part of amuseum's  collection.

Made in London
Jasper, cast and hand-finished
fields.history_note: Trophy was a temporary installation in the Cast Courts of the V&A on 29th of September 2006
